3. FMATTACK: FIVE ATTACK CLASSES

3.1 Direct Attacks (Spec-Allowed)

ID Attack FMAPI Commands Property Violated
ATK-1 Cross-tenant device hijack UNBIND_VPPB (victim) + BIND_VPPB (attacker) Confinement
ATK-2 Fabric DoS SET_PHY_PORT_STATE(port=victim, state=DOWN) Availability
ATK-3 DCD memory theft DCD_RELEASE(extent=victim) + DCD_ADD(extent, tenant=attacker) Confinement

Example (ATK-3 in TLA+):

```tla
ATTACK_DCD_Theft ==
  /\ victimExtent \in VictimExtents
  /\ FM!DCD_Release(victimExtent)  \* No zeroing required by spec
  /\ FM!DCD_Add(victimExtent, attacker)
  /\ UNCHANGED <<...>>
```

3.2 Compositional Attacks (Novel)

ATK-4: Ownership Inversion Attack
Victim allocates E1 (offset 0-1GB), attacker allocates E2 (1GB-2GB) overlapping same physical device. Attacker releases E2. Victim reads E1 but device returns stale data from E2 due to lack of physical zeroing.

ATK-5: Control-Plane Exhaustion
Attacker repeatedly sends BIND_VPPB/UNBIND_VPPB on a single vPPB. FM re-runs topology discovery each time (O(N²) complexity). With 100 commands/sec, FM CPU reaches 94%.

Table I: Attack Characteristics

Attack Precondition Latency (μs) Success Rate
