10. CONCLUSION

This paper presented the first formal security analysis of the CXL Fabric Manager control plane. We modeled FMAPI as a state machine, identified five attack classes (including two novel compositional attacks), and proved using TLA+ that the baseline CXL specification permits all five. We then proposed ZTFM, a zero-trust reference monitor with SPDM-bound authentication, ownership invariants, and verified policy enforcement. Experimental evaluation on a high-fidelity emulator—combined with formal verification—shows ZTFM blocks all attacks with <5μs overhead and maintains availability under attack. We release the first open-source artifact for CXL FM security, demonstrating that the vulnerability is architectural and can be mitigated without hardware changes.

Takeaway: The CXL ecosystem must extend SPDM-style security to the control plane, not just the data plane.

